The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", published a brochure
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several common features.
Rather, they belong to the older generation, they cannot get involved in work for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
The one who "becomes" a witch is sent to isolation so as not to endanger the rest of the village.
"Man seldom has this fate."
“Young, healthy women don’t give up, either, because they help at work and give birth to children,” describes a nun in the West African state capital of Burkina Faso who takes care of more than a hundred women who have been expelled by their community in a special home.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She has published an information brochure to help curb the witch hunt.
But there's a catch.
“More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso can’t read,” Die Standard said in a statement.
Witchcraft accusations are common in other African countries.
In Burkina Faso’s neighbouring country of Ghana, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week after being tortured, spilled petroleum and set on fire by three women and two men.
The case was reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators say it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, the woman was ignited with oil, which is used for ritual anointing.
He said the group was trying to "expel the evil spirit from the woman."
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of the level of education attained.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devouring of human souls has always been a danger.”
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to ease the witch-hunt, in Gambia the president himself participated in it last year.
"Gambian President Jammy has launched a massive witch hunt after his aunt's death, allegedly to take part in her death and attempt to use black magic to kill the president himself."
"He has called on shamans from nearby Guinea to help him, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's personal security, have forcibly taken randomly selected men and women from Gambia's villages to the president's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in a statement.
On the farm, the imprisoned people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
The two imprisoned did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, nearly a thousand prisoners were finally released.
Bakal's tenant drowns in stoves, higher rent signed
An elderly man stepped out of the door of the client center of the company RPG Byty "uglobaron" Zden<0xC4><0x9B>k Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried a file with new lease agreements for three apartments: his own, his daughter and his son, who is in custody.
For all three, deregulation just raised the rent.
Instead of 3,500 a month, the son will pay CZK 4,100 for an apartment 2+1 of the second category from next year.
"And there is no hot water there, and it must be melted by petrama," the man points with his finger in his son's new contract, whose signature he has the power to sign.
"But I signed," he explains, half angry and half resigned.
