The offices also include a kindergarten, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect that it also hides a mini-schooler with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it has been open to children of Arch.Design employees.
The architectural design company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings arose, has been counting on space for its corporate mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs nearly 90 people, mostly of babyboom age, and cares about getting women designers and architects back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of part-time work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of a social program.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine demanding work with child care.
The mini-school was invented by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the grant funding (a subsidy of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and provide qualified personnel and operations for two years.
After the financial subsidy (2 years) is exhausted, Arch.Design is obliged to operate the mini-school for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of the project took one year and the application for a subsidy was greatly assisted by the company Economy Rating.
Care is provided by qualified staff, the children are taken care of all day by a nurse and a primary school teacher, so children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, yet most of them are over 3 years old.
Since it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day there are more children.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation for school benches, English is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and stressful situations with delayed pick-up of children from kindergartens far from the parents' workplace are eliminated.
Parents are more productive in their working hours.
It is not surprising that a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship is created here.
Arch.Design has thus become one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program have strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look into Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its organic shapes, the house was nicknamed the House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí’s Art Nouveau.
The front of the house is filled with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
Detailed observation shows geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of colors is further enhanced.
Curls and twists of shapes appear equally in interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, eyelets and rails.
Located in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Gràcia 43, the Batlló House was rebuilt in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the apartment house Casa Batlló himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated with him.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property were created, as well as the use of mosaics on the facade.
A number of other artists and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs of the Casa Batlló house started the successful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and Güell Park, which contains Gaudí's other works.
From the locals, the house soon after completion, thanks to its organic shapes, earned the nickname "House of Bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening windows, began to call it a "living house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for his time, with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five degree slope.
When creating Gaudí absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he received a building permit from the city, but the information about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, during the completion, the city council was appalled by the result and asked for correction.
The councillors were concerned, for example, that the building interfered with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
Corrections never took place, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the appeal of the city district, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
The gallery on the second floor was a lounge and on the third floor was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewellery store.
The whole six-storey house intersects the staircase, which can be climbed to the roof terrace.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon door, and the larger company can communicate comfortably with each other without preserving the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí’s reconstruction also received an unconventional roof and two additional floors.
Also impressive is Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which is lined with the inner courtyard, and skylights.
The game of two colors adds a maximum of light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and luxurious apartment is open to the public.
The owners decided on this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed at the tours because they found it to be a very profitable business, and in addition, they extended the tours to common and attic areas, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is certainly not negligible, it is 16,50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you need to quickly make friends with one of the residents of the apartment and visit it right at home.
How to choose a mattress and grate: women have different requirements than men
Not the sumptuous frame of the bed, but the quality of the lying surface, that is, the mattress and the grate, give the basis of a really good bed.
However, they must be harmoniously complemented to suit a specific user.
When choosing, a lot of things decide, from weight, height, age, health status and gender of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattresses and grates are made.
Typical example?
For example, latex mattresses are not suitable for weekend cottages, where they do not regularly heat up, because they "warm up" more slowly.
In addition, they have a significantly higher weight than a standard polyurethane mattress.
However, it is necessary to turn them regularly.
If they do not have a lot of venting ducts in the core, and still lie on a solid plate, they retain moisture: even mold could appear under them.
The habit also determines the choice.
Those who have spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel good on low and with a hard surface.
"Maybe all the hockey players coming back from the NHL complained to me that they weren't going to sleep here."
"They needed a mattress with a softening layer of lazy foam for their battered shoulders, heels, and hips."
"Such people are recommended even for people with diabetes who have a disorder of the nervous system, so they do not receive 'information' from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamczik, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Therefore, many hockey players, as well as other customers, have been looking for a mattress with lazy foam for years.
"Today it's cool, a suitable mattress has, for example, Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico."
You don't have to be an NHL fighter to appreciate lazy foam.
This "miracle" works simply.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the absorbed heat, or adapts to your warm body.
Nothing is pushing you, you will not roll over at night like after a hard fight.
You'll just get a better night's sleep.
Lazy foam also acts as a protection against bedsores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of the foot to your height, which is usually about 21 to 34 cm.
A man and a woman with a height of about 180 cm need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double bed, i.e. 180 cm in total.
For single beds, such as singles, it is recommended to have at least 120 to 140 cm.
For convenience and a possible visit.
"Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly bent at the elbow," advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, guildmaster of the Guild of upholsterers and decorators, who has been dealing with the issue of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for many years and lectures it at professional schools.
For a double bed, everyone needs their own grid and mattress, but here, be careful when buying to match the heights of the mattress.
Otherwise, there will be nothing left but to mount the grilles to different heights, but this may not be possible for every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a spring skeleton of at least 15, of which at least three centimeters count on a molding and boiling layer.
"When touching your hands or sitting on a mattress, you must definitely not feel the springs," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of grating.
Full-furnished beds, where the mattresses and the base are like fused Siamese twins, have nothing to do in the bedrooms.
Mattresses are poorly ventilated, you can not wash their cover, which is already common today.
And since we usually sweat 0.2 to 0.75 liters of sweat per night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will begin to resemble one large (and clogged) sieve.
That’s why experts reject advertising slogans about mattress lifespans of up to 25 years, or even lifetime guarantees.
But everything has its buts.
That’s why the practical advice from the sellers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, do not give up hygiene and washable coating, but add a mattress protector, which can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers with zippers are commonly produced around the perimeter today, so after unlocking we get two parts (for washing and size of the washing machine very important!), still handling in larger types (and in one person) during shooting could resemble a duel of lightweight in the ring with heavy.
Do you have a solid board in bed instead of a grill?
Never! Never!
Maximum for a bed intended for one-night visits.
However, still provide the board (if it does not already have one) with ventilation holes and use a mattress with a spring frame and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (of it.Taschenfederkern) and a boiling layer.
A polyurethane mattress does not belong on such a substrate.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (such as a combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable for non-positioning slatted grates with 14 to 18 slats, but you always pay for grates with more slats, 28 or more, where the slats in the hip area are doubled and their rigidity can be regulated.
The spring-skeleton mattresses do not belong to the positioning lamellar grates because they do not react to the positioning.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the slats, the so-called shoulder cradle can also be indulged.
It is a special lamella fastening that allows you to push or even tilt the lamella so that the sleeping arm is nicely "hollowed".
For men who have "shoulders over the whole back" is definitely an important thing.
Even mattress manufacturers already remember it, who in the "men's" began to use a softening zone just in the area of the shoulders.
Women are also remembered - they in turn indulge in a softer surface in the places of the hips.
For the most demanding customers are designed winged or plate gratings with so-called multi-torsion springing.
The pressure breaks down into more points and the tension decreases.
However, be careful, once you use the wrong mattress and grid cushion (large and "puffy"), most of the "plus" will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and only touch the shoulders with the tips so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
As a suitable size is recommended 50 x 60 cm, which is preferred, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should level (along with the shoulder cradle of the grate or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original grass-filled straw mattresses.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least additives.
The trend is also in mattresses.
The raw materials from petroleum, from which polyurethane foams are made, are replaced by natural oils, for example, from jumper and soybeans.
All known manufacturers use soybeans.
"Bio in mattresses means that the core is made of a material of purely natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1>í<0xC4><0x8D>ek from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers, one of the first being aloe vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules to release the fresh scent of forest or lavender.
There is also a division between men and women.
While men are “cooled” by a plant extract from birch so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women, on the other hand, “heat” the covers.
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making the weaker sex warmer.
Today's favorites?
A mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with broken cellular structure, it is thus more breathable than conventional polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
The combination of different stiffnesses of cold foam and "lazy" foam creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels should be.
For a quality mattress you will pay from seven thousand crowns and above.
Those who meet health parameters, have a lower VAT rate, are taken as medical aids.
Gumotex was the first to achieve this advantage in the Czech Republic.
Saving on mattress and grate is not easy.
Sometimes you can use the actions of manufacturers or sellers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers a Duofreeze mattress with sewn Memory foam into the cover for CZK 11,990.
The second one can be purchased for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cellular structure and high density was started by Tempur material at a "cosmic" pace.
It was originally created as a material for NASA because the astronauts were subjected to enormous overload during the launches.
Tempur softens in the heat, on the contrary, it hardens in the cold.
Thus, it perfectly adapts to the warm human body and distributes its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal against the appearance of bedsores, but also to increase sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only on mattresses, but also on medical products, such as special pillows under the legs, which relieve the legs and the venous system.
Domestic manufacturers use, for example, Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents want to watch their children.
Fear for your own child is driving more and more people to the idea of babysitting via GPS.
The system originally created for searching for cars can also track the movement of people, and thus help in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
A number of people were terrified by the case of missing Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka and began to search for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood that a tragedy will happen," said Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases such devices may be misused, for example, if they are put in a bag by someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Most of the time, customers actually buy it for safety reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in case of an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková points out that if a child does not want to wear anything like this, he will simply get rid of it.
“Even very young children show great creativity in how to intentionally lose some things when they don’t want to be in control.”
"Mobile phones were previously high expectations for parents, but they can be turned off in the same way as these tracking devices," says Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such a facility would actually help in the event of an attack.
"When it comes to a planned abduction, the perpetrator will almost always ensure that the child does not have any electronics with him that could reveal his location."
"Now it's a phone."
"As tracking devices begin to expand, they will look for them as well, because their sales will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In this case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
