Longer index finger than ring finger indicates lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than a ring finger are less likely to develop prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men under 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly when combined with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and more than 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
More than half of the participants in the study had an index finger on their right hand shorter than a ring finger.
They were as likely to have prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, for those who had the index finger longer than the ring finger, the risk decreased by 33 percent, while for men in their 60s it decreased by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Earlier research has shown that testosterone promotes the growth of prostate cancer.
Professor Václav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that he was briefly aware of the study, but did not believe that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "fully proven".
