The Common Practice of Democracy
Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the support for private entrepreneurship.
Criminal activity is more worrying than unemployment.
And Brazil is considered by many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current Latinobarómetro survey, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
This year’s survey, which took place in September and early October, is dominated by two related issues.
The first is that Latin America is in a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several Pacific periphery countries in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy was recovering from a deep decline in output last year.
But only about half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas, are convinced Democrats, downplaying the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, this is a large increase (Figure 3).
Approximately 34% said they trusted the parliament in their country and 45% trusted the government, again the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
Support arose during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the proportion of Latinos living in poverty rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
However, the mood varies from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has worsened.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important problem rather than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say either they themselves or their close relatives became victims of crime last year, but that’s down from 38% last year and is also the lowest figure since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in growing support for private entrepreneurship and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents across the region say that private entrepreneurship is essential for development, this percentage increased from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that a market economy is the only system that will enable their country’s development, up from 47% last year.
