It's not like that.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry, and that a set of elements we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explains Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element with another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't an accident.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it shows high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she considered that a microbe that is exposed to both elements may be able to replace one after the other.
"Arsene is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, it is very difficult for organisms to separate these elements."
"However, arsenic is so different that, like phosphorus, it does not work. Once it gets into the body, it begins to work in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to an increasing concentration of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt to and grow.
Microbes grow better when exposed to phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the possibility that a life form that uses arsenic may occur naturally increases, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic being replaced by phosphorus was not new, but there was never an example to prove it.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and scientists speculated that it could have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
