U.S. Attorneys Won't Blame Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Justice Department have cleared Senator John Ensigna of criminal charges related to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure a lobby, his lawyers said on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat Mr. Ensign, a Nevada Republican, has faced and was, until the time of the scandal, considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012. His affair made national headlines and damaged his career.
Mr Ensign's office said it was "certainly pleased" with the decision, which followed almost a year of investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary proceedings before the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department “has informed us that Senator Ensign will no longer be the target of the investigation and that there is no plan to bring further charges against him in this matter.”
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The decision came as a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Justice Department, who claimed there was substantial evidence that Mr. Ensign was preparing to violate a federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents published in October 2009 in the New York Times reported that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure a lucrative lobby that was supposed to lead to the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator’s affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer in the Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political supporters to find a job for Mr. Hampton and supported their views after Mr. Hampton was hired to lobby for them, so much so as to cite documents and interviews.
Since Hampton was until recently Mr. Ensign's assistant, he was banned from lobbying his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts claim that the unusual settlement of Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared in violation of the lobbying ban.
The evidence that was released "shows that this is a clear case of preparing a violation of the law," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients who are being investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the Department was cautious about political lawsuits after a number of setbacks, including last year's decision to suspend the lawsuit against former Senator Ted Stevens for questioning the state's indictment.
Federal prosecutors “clearly hid guns,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a group of lawyers who filed several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"It basically indicates that high-ranking government officials are not covered by the law," she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign’s chief lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from the Justice Department’s attorney general on Monday and then the next day, telling him that the department had found no charges against his client.
Mr Ensign’s defense team is working with prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he forwarded to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable detailing my discussions with the Department of Justice except that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to close an investigation into a separate complaint in which an ethical group accused Ensign’s parents’ $96,000 payment to the Hamptons of violating federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that money meant nothing but a gift.
One company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work was NV Energy, a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator.
One December 2008 email showed that after Mr. Hampton began working as a lobbyist at the company, Mr. Ensign's employee manager, John Lopez, communicated with Mr. Hampton and told him that he had "drilled" into the Home Office about the subject being discussed.
Mr. Ensign also attended lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and invited the Minister of Transport to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after they hired Mr. Hampton for lobbying work.
When the scandal first surfaced last year, Mr Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After months of stagnation, Mr Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
In a report that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman Jennifer Cooper said the senator hopes the ethics committee will quickly follow the Justice Department and close the entire investigation.
“Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing her hard work on behalf of the Nevada people,” she said.
