Can politeness overcome the abyss?
After a campaign that was notable for its offensiveness and negativity, a small amount of politeness emerged in Washington this week.
Is this the first sign of genuine cooperation between the two political parties, or just an illusory moment before a quick return to the party struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and parliamentary leaders brought no major breakthroughs on the crucial issues that need to be discussed during the meeting.
In any case, however, it was a polite discussion about the differences of opinion between the two parties, as well as the definition of their joint responsibilities, rather than another empty episode of party struggle.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that close cooperation over several months has built mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still divides the members.
And it is quite difficult to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in probation - probing each other's signs of collegiality and compromise, trying to assess the boundaries of public opinion and voter patience towards a renewed party war.
Therefore, Tuesday’s meeting and its later assessment by the participants was also carried out with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too wide and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the conditions that have prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s about taxes, spending, health care or rights, both sides are miles apart.
However, the November elections were prepared by Washington at least quickly.
"It's not a question of whether regulatory issues have changed," said Pete Wehner, Bush's administrator, now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"These are inevitable after the elections.
The election stirred the emotions of the parties, and they then quieted.
It's good."
On several issues, especially those to be discussed in the session, Republicans and Democrats have little chance of finding a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts at the end of the year have expired, and no one considers it favorable.
Both sides want to find a way to protect some or all, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, a likely compromise on unemployment benefits is just because Republicans can’t watch how they support tax cuts for the wealthy while denying unemployment benefits to the unemployed.
After Tuesday's White House talks, there is already more optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of the new opening treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful collaboration on critical issues will not necessarily lead to a two-party relationship when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable, he said.
"Once the things that have to be done are done, psychology will return to one of the confrontations in the short run," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism - which is largely widespread - that politeness will lead them to genuine cooperation.
“I look at everything that’s going on between now and 2012 as a shadow box when the main events happen in 2012,” he said.
The reasons are largely related to the formation of a new Republican majority in the White House and the Tea Party voters who helped create it.
Republican leaders now face the danger of exaggeration, knowing that they must act on their promises and must cut government spending and repeal the new health care law.
These supportive lines are clear in the initial responses to the deficit recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and reducing spending.
Joint chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest tasks in Washington and have, in their view, put pressure on the deficit issue to public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in an 18-member commission to present their plan as an official recommendation and fight to get as close to that number as possible.
The biggest resistance is among the elected officials on the jury, who suggest that, in the case of financial issues, at least today, we have little basis or the will to compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House and parliamentary Republicans.
The first will start next year in the form of party conflicts, when Republicans will call on Obama to address budgets, taxes and healthcare, followed by a period of greater party cooperation.
What will cause the shift?
The public opinion.
There is plenty of evidence that, despite being partisan in the last election, most Americans still want to see two parties working together.
If it could go to a heel, as it was in 1995, then both sides will be very closely watching the public reaction.
Anyone who is threatened with a vote cut is likely to change course and seek a compromise.
This can be an optimistic view of things.
The partisanship and orientation is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and it turns out that there is a greater ideological gap between Obama and the parliamentary Republicans than there was with the Republicans and Bill Clinton.
At the same time, activists on both sides see 2010 as a prelude to more important elections in 2012.
Based on this reality, the politeness that has emerged this week would be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will cost a lot of effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
U.S. Document Describes Moscow as a Refuge of Corruption
The administration of the city is in the hands of “kleptocracy” and it continues with part of the bribes and protection bribes that come on the way to the Kremlin, the US embassy in Russia said in February records.
Both the police and the Federal Security Service largely hold protective wings that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – which Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical of the office” – takes its toll when money starts moving up the ladder.
The recording, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published on Wednesday via WikiLeaks on their website.
The record is based on the sources whose names have been redacted.
The record was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor and accuses him of a large share of corruption.
He was impeached in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but since then we have seen only minimal changes in purges.
Luzhkov and his wife Yelena Baturina, who owns a prominent design firm, have repeatedly denied corruption allegations for many years, and won several lawsuits on false charges for such accusations.
In September, he told a Russian TV station when asked about the evidence of corruption: “It’s crazy, it’s filth, it’s filth.”
The Russians believe with absolute conviction that if their society is corrupt, it will show up in a vote.
However, it is unusual to see such details spoken in such a way, in an embassy report, and it is also unheard of for diplomats from foreign countries to do so.
“The Moscow city government and its connections to criminal elements have led some to call it ‘disfunctional,’ and confirm that the government operates more like a kleptocracy than a government,” the report says.
“Criminal elements enjoy the so-called ‘krysha’ (a term from the world of crime and mafia, which literally means ‘roof’ or protection) provided by the police, the Federal Security Service, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior and the Public Prosecutor’s Office, as well as everywhere in the government bureaucracy of the city of Moscow.
"Analysts have identified a three-stage structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the very top."
"Federal Security Service, Home Office and Militia are on the second level."
"Finally, at the lowest level are ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors."
“It’s an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill in the blanks in some areas because the city does not provide some services.”
The report says the FSB is taking money from the biggest companies and the police are targeting smaller businesses.
One source said, “Moscow shop owners realize that it is better to get protection from the FSB or the Ministry of the Interior (rather than organized criminal groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and strength than criminal groups, but are also protected by law.”
"That's why protection from criminal gangs is no longer on the line."
The record says that while the withdrawal of money is complex, the protection itself can already be in trouble; even those who pay can sometimes be arrested.
For those who do not pay fast enough, their stores are closed under various pretexts.
Medvedev has repeatedly spoken about the fight against corruption, but has admitted that he has made little progress.
The embassy report speaks of men taking suitcases, probably packed with cash, into the Kremlin itself.
“In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on bureaucrats,” said Georgy Satarov, director of Moscow’s Indem research team, in a recent interview.
“It’s part of the bureaucracy.”
He is not a member of a political class because there are no longer any political classes in Russia.
Without politicians, without opposition, without power-sharing, corruption is inevitable, he said.
Indem estimates that nationwide corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent survey on the global perception of corruption by the NGO Transparency International (countries ranked from least to most corrupt).
The unveiling of the U.S. embassy report, which appeared in Moscow only in the late evening, certainly did not stir the Russian government’s enthusiasm, although only to the extent that Luzhkov could be blamed for Moscow’s shortcomings, it may be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue on the issue of resolving the problem.
In an interview with CNN with Larry King, Putin said the documents WikiLeaks published could have been forged and reacted angrily to statements that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this is about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he said.
"But to be honest, we didn't think it would be done with such arrogance, with such pressure, you know, so unethical."
Veterans of the Khmer Rouge are forced to deal with the past
In a sparingly lit concrete classroom with stained and peeled walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who built it, the leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves the Moka."
"He was a good leader and took care of his people," Sreng Kor Ma, 42, said.
Known as the “butcher” for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote Khmer Rouge state in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge relinquished power, long-standing loyalty is also broken in Anlong Veng.
In April, victims at the Truth and Reconciliation Forum were allowed to publicly confront people who were part of the regime.
In June, the government provided textbooks that for the first time explain to children the history of the Khmer Rouge and their former soldiers.
And in July, jointly by the UN and the Cambodian Court, the first conviction of a former member of the Khmer Rouge, the sentencing of the former leader of the notorious violent association Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Ghost, to 35 years in prison.
With each such advancement, unrest grew among the Khmer Rouge veterans in Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to rejoin Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia’s documentation center, an independent organization that studies the regime.
"For them, life among the Khmer Rouge was wonderful, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It divides families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its soldiers fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla wars from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal, the country was led to the first democratic elections in 1993. Large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to transition to a government that culminated in the capitulation of Ieng Sara in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who persevered, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters had fallen into the ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgically remember the time of the movement.
Although several of the elite Khmer Rouge have maintained their local government position in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak as unskilled farmers.
"These people benefited only minimally from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are surrounded by the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They were upbringing without any idea of doing business."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling down as a poor farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"The Mok nourished them all."
"But now life is hard, because we have to take care of everything ourselves."
The ongoing trial of the Khmer Rouge has also raised concerns.
At the beginning of next year, the court will start investigating Nuon Che, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court has a mandate to prosecute leading perpetrators and those responsible for the crimes, but it has not been said whether it will continue in the four cases.
It was little to appease the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation centered on Im Chaema, 64, who was a regional leader in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Documentation Centre in Cambodia that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that likely killed thousands of forced laborers.
On a recent steamy evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the field to her wooden house on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun began to descend and shadows appeared over the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about her past among the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to go.
"There is peace in Cambodia and it is stable," she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court searches for more suspects, although experts and historians disagree.
"Cambodia must dig a deep hole and bury the past in it," he said.
But confronting the past is just what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
"Reconciliation in Khmer proportions means sticking together broken pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand each other."
The center published the first textbook approved by the government about the Khmer Rouge, it has 75 pages and the title "History of Democratic Cambodia."
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as an addendum to the Department of Education's history textbook, which contains less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
Like many people in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng knew few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's connection with the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a high school student at Anlong Veng said the new textbook helps students understand important parts of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he took home the book for study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the courts," he said.
"They're suspicious because they're not sure how many people will be prosecuted."
Such resistance makes the process of reconciliation more complicated and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, textbooks and the court are starting to have an impact, he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a strong charm here.
Upstairs in the Dangrek Mountains is a weed-covered road sprinkled with thrown plastic bags that leads to a black soot rectangle covered with a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone saleswoman on the side of the road, said she didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit, many local people come here and pray to him," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and she planned to visit Pol Pot's resting place later, where she would bring a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope that it would bring her luck.
Belarus agrees to appear to have stockpiled uranium-based weapons
In a surprise victory in President Obama’s campaign to secure nuclear material around the world, the Belarusian government announced on Wednesday that it would give up its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The agreement was made public in a joint statement issued after a security summit between Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton and Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov.
For years, the U.S. government has been trying to convince Belarus to give up highly enriched uranium, and it seemed that they hit the rock last spring.
But U.S. officials told The Washington Post that a couple of clandestine operations have been carried out with Belarus over the past two months to remove 187 pounds of uranium-based weapons from a Belarusian research facility.
This set the stage for Wednesday's deal to remove the remainder of the material - about <0xC2><0xA3>500, according to an official who spoke on condition of anonymity, as this is a sensitive matter.
The agreement proved to be one of the most important outcomes of Obama’s 47th National Nuclear Security Summit in April, at which Belarus was excluded.
And it was probably a good move to secure an invitation for the former Soviet Republic to the ensuing summit in 2012.
"I was really fascinated by the fact that they want a place at the 2012 Nuclear Safety Summit."
“This proves that the process is working,” said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for Global Security, a group supporting nuclear safety.
Clinton called the deal a "very significant, important step" from Belarus.
In April 2009, Obama pledged to secure all sensitive nuclear materials worldwide within four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries dispose of all their stockpiles of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will be seventh.
Dozens of countries did so under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of the Obama summit on nuclear security, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko announced that his nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially the basis for the weapon and less enriched uranium," Lukashenko said.
“It’s our commodity... We’re not going to make dirty bombs and we’re not going to sell it to anyone.”
"We only use it for research purposes, that's all."
However, Belarus acceded to the United States a few months ago and has shown interest in reaching an agreement.
The first commitment to remove Belarusian uranium in October was particularly complicated because the material was lightly irradiated, officials said.
It was loaded onto a special train that traveled more than 1,300 miles to a Russian storage and disposal facility, officials said.
The second operation was closed on Monday and was carried out by air, officials said.
The U.S. government spent $13 million on the program, most of it on supplying less enriched uranium to the Belarusian research institute, which is not suitable for the production of nuclear weapons.
“Everything was coordinated very carefully and managed on a basis of trust,” which led to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, an official at the Department of Energy working for Global Threat Reduction.
The James Martin Center for Nuclear Non-Proliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus has at least 88 pounds of uranium usable for weapons production.
According to the joint statement, Belarus will seek to remove its stocks by 2012.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been tense for years, mainly because of Lukashenko's brutal repression of human rights.
But Wednesday's statement suggests the possibility of a gradual meltdown.
"We welcome progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus have recognized that more consistent respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains the basis for improving mutual relations and this is necessary for the progress of the country and its people," he said.
