This is according to documents provided by Wikileaks to the newspaper El País, which also says that the then First Deputy Prime Minister María Teresa Fernández de la Vega requested that the Spanish executive be informed and "so could show that it has proper supervision of foreign aircraft flying through Spanish airspace".
In June 2006, following a Council of Europe communication accusing a dozen countries, including Spain, of complicity in human rights violations, a meeting took place between US Ambassador Eduardo Aguirre and Fernández de la Vega.
The deputy prime minister said the Council of Europe's announcement "put the Zapatero government out of the game" and insisted Spain had nothing to hide in the matter.
De la Vega stressed that Spain has no problem with the flights of secret services through its territory.
"They simply want to be informed" so that they are not "caught unprepared," Aguirre said in one of the documents.
The then foreign minister, Miguel <0xC3><0x81>ngel Moratinos, also hinted to the U.S. ambassador that the Spanish government "wanted to give the matter the lowest possible outline, but by the fact that the matter was in the hands of the judges, the cabinet had limited powers of influence."
In February 2007, Attorney General Vicente González told the Embassy that, as far as he was concerned, he had no intention of blocking the judge's initiative to request the declassification of documents of the National Intelligence Center (CNI) and the Department of Defense relating to CIA flights.
"This information does not contain any incriminated file or any sensitive information," the embassy said in a statement.
However, the U.S. has expressed concerns about "apparent coordination between the Spanish judge and German prosecutors" rather than the declassification of information by the CNI or the Department of Defense.
“This coordination between independent experts will complicate our efforts to resolve this case discreetly between governments,” Aguirre said.
In March 2007, on the occasion of the lunch of the U.S. Ambassador and Secretary of the Interior Alfred Pérez Rubalcaba, the ambassador said that "although the Spanish judges are very jealous of their independence and will do what they deem appropriate," he had already instructed his colleagues to "avoid the intentional fires."
The Ambassador also expresses his concern about the actions of the Popular Party (PP) in this matter.
“Despite its general pro-American orientation, our experience tells us that the Popular Party will not hesitate to exploit any indication that the Zapatero government has tolerated or deliberately ignored U.S. actions that could be interpreted as possible human rights violations, even if these disclosures could have negative consequences for the U.S. government.”
