Red Bull Triumphs in Formula 1 With Siemens’ Secret Weapon
The software suggests improvements in vehicles in real time.
Since Red Bull entered the Formula One series in 2004, its history in this extraordinary world of speed has been characterized by surprise and success.
At first, no one took the possibilities of this newly arrived team very seriously, and despite the recent upward trend, everyone was betting on Fernando Alonso’s Ferrari triumph.
Without wanting to diminish the riding abilities of the champion, German Sebastian Vettel, or the power of the Renault engine that drives his car, a legend was born in the world of Formula One - a "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens placed in the hands of Red Bull to make him a winning team.
In fact, it is a powerful software simulating marches, which the German company launched in 2007 for the purposes of very remote motorsport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, has been used to design assembly lines at production plants around the world, in power plants and for high-precision instruments.
Its goal is to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary mistakes and expenses.
The PLM facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of industrial division at Siemens, explains that the use of this software device has allowed the Red Bull team to carry out modifications and improvements that are otherwise detected during races and tests "within a few hours, in almost real time."
Russwurm says that in 1992, stables employed an average of 10 technicians who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements in a single period.
Today, the Red Bull team is working with 180 young, highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology to analyze and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The head of Siemens explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of Red Bull racing vehicles except the engine, for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be converted from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced laser manufacturing systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this technical capability is $40 million, representing the maximum that each Formula 1 team can spend for each period to improve their competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up a high-tech race to design and build its racing cars around 50km from London.
These are two buildings that are restricted to visits - especially to journalists.
Everything that happens here is considered a “great secret.”
The list of participants in this project includes 580 people, including two pilots - champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of Red Bull in Formula 1 is, without a doubt, fresh champion Sebastian Vettel.
However, behind the immense technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has put into its participation in racing circuits, there are other protagonists whose help is invaluable, and yet no one knows them.
Steve Nevey, head of manufacturing technology, said that five years ago it was possible to say that advances in vehicle research and development contributed to the victory by 50%, and the rest was thanks to the riders.
At present, this ratio has changed and the technology is worth the success of 85%, while the pilots contribute 15%.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computing, as they are "unpredictable gladiators".
