The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary zone, in which states that violate the rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to announce deferrals of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the costs.
Germany is telling us that we need to go down a strict growth path with increased savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
Another option based on receivables and construction, with the huge gaps in the balance of payments that prevailed in the years of Spain’s growth boom, they simply do not intend to tolerate.
The offer is clear.
