Sport and bypassing the rules
The tricks Alonso and Ramos played against Ajax show ingenuity, not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November caused a sea of ink to be listed on whether this is unsportsmanlike behaviour and whether UEFA should punish both players.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team had clearly won), the appointed players deliberately lost time one by one when a foul was about to take place in order to provoke the referee, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending in their group in the lead - and will be able to proceed, deprived of cards, to the next stage.
Eventually, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sentenced Coach José Mourinho to two matches and fined the offenders.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, rules that are unwritten but are followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that Real Madrid (which boasts of generosity and honor in its anthem, and which has already fined its players for similar acts) and, it seems, also due to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history of comedian and provocateur.
in any case, the debate is about whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether it circumvents the law; indeed, it is an action which respects the rules of sport, the purpose of which, of course, seems to seek to circumvent.
It deals with the type of damage that such actions cause to the sports spirit.
One of the essentials of sports behavior is the physical integrity of the opponents, which in these cases was not violated, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these neat game features is to avoid giving players an advantage over the opposing team due to their misdemeanor – which hasn’t happened here either.
Therefore, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as deception or circumvention of the law did not happen, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should have been as obvious as possible in order to receive a penalty.
They waited and enjoyed being punished.
Another question, however, is what advantage the guilty will have from their deliberate wrongdoing.
Here it must be stated that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that there is no benefit in the current match, since the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And it is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in a future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, that is, at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition to this, the players will be sentenced, and move to the second round of cards, in which it is enough to exclude one card less than in the first round.
So as the rounds continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
In the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid a penalty (which would be a clear circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and circumvention of the rules is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly ingenuity.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because there were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions to provoke them were transmitted from the leadership.
Damage to sporting principles by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
