The United States is changing the rules for issuing visas
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centres before interviewing at the Consular Section; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Service Centres (abbreviated as ASC) before interviewing the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will collect the applicant’s biometric information, which will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay a fee for arranging a meeting, another for processing the application and another for delivering the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only a single fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since biometric information will be taken from the ASC, applicants who will require a second appointment with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an additional $26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
