World Lighting Renewal Plan
The United Nations has proposed a plan in Cancun to restore home, shop and industrial lighting in 100 countries with the aim of achieving greenhouse gas (GES) reductions, which correspond to almost one-third of the additional limit to be achieved to stabilize the planet’s climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to implement in Cancún to compensate for the lack of difficult-to-implement reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace the incandescent bulbs that monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market with fluocompact bulbs or, even better, bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a significant amount of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet generated due to lighting would be decommissioned.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70% of the world’s car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance to achieve by 2020 the stabilization of the climate warming at 2 degrees Celsius to be able to exclude that it will not get out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat, and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL bulbs, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs introduced this week by Philips — the company reportedly participated in a UN study — have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving us an idea of possible savings with a replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact lamps because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless producers set up collection centres.
However, the report states that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluocompact incandescent bulb, but rather thermal coal power plants, which emit much of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these headquarters put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation annually.
The report also details the profits that each country would make from this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants, the construction of which would cost 2.5 billion.
