Vengeful hackers and hardworking spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, an obvious scandal is uncovered, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and anticipates the future controlled by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the Secret Service (of any nation) consists entirely of press cuts.
The "extraordinary revelations" of Americans about Berlusconi's sexual life are announcing what for months everyone could read in any newspaper (all but these two Berlusconi own), and the notorious cartoon profile of Gaddafi has long been a subject for sketch cabaret artists.
The rule that secret documents can only consist of messages already known is essential in the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a bookstore that deals with esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Masons) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
Not only because the author of occult texts does not like to look for new information (or even know where to look for reports about the non-existent), but because those who are engaged in occultism believe only what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
That's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same applies to secret documents.
The informant is lazy, and the lazy (or limited in spirit) head of the secret services (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, the editor of the newspaper Libération) who only considers what he admits to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy sent to the State Department was the same information that Newsweek had published a week earlier.
So why was there so much fuss about the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely, that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War and since the time when heads of state can call each other or fly off to dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have transformed into espionage centers.
Any viewer watching films about the investigation knows very well that it is only out of hypocrisy that it seems to be ignored.
However, the fact that this is repeated publicly blasphemes the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain top-secret information from the most powerful country in the world is a hard blow, not negligible, to the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victims and its "executors".
But let's move on from here to the deep truth of what happened.
Once upon a time, in the days of Orwell, it was possible to contain all power, like some Big Brother who controlled every movement of his people.
Orwell’s prophecy has been proven ever since, thanks to the ability to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the motorway used, and so on, the citizen became a total victim of the wreath of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now,that even "tombs" with the most secret information of the powerful can not resist the intervention of some hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker—elected as the avenger of the citizen—can know all the secrets of power.
How can he keep a power that can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that the real secret is an unsubstantiated secret (and an unsubstantiated secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious unsubstantiated secret, because it is extracted from public life; but to reveal all secrets was, as it was to him by Hillary, a secret without Cleopatra.
WikiLeaks did not make any mistakes with Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big to Clinton and Obama.
What will the consequences of this blow of the bestowal of the Power be so significant?
It is clear that in the future, states will not be able to send online sensitive information - that would be the equivalent of posting it on a poster on a street corner.
But it’s also quite obvious that with current technology, it’s useless to hope that you can keep a message confidential over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when the head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and sensitive messages be kept confidential in the future?
I know my prognosis is science fiction at the moment, so it's fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials transporting themselves discreetly fulfilling formalities along uncontrollable routes, carrying only those messages that they know by heart, or rather hide rare information in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be preserved in unique copies in key-sealed drawers: overall, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways forward, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet rehabilitated wire-based telegraph.
Videotapes (analogues) allowed cinema lovers to shoot a movie step by step, moving it forward and backwards and uncovering all the secrets of assembly, whereas now CDs (digital) only allow you to jump through chapters, that is, macro portions.
By high-speed trains, we reach Milan in three hours, while it takes three and a half hours to travel by plane and transport.
It is not unusual, therefore, that politics and communication technologies will return to horse-drawn chariots.
One final comment.
At other times, the press tried to understand what was being set up in the secret of the embassy.
Now it is embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: How France hacked its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test the promises of fast-start or early-start funding made by developed countries.
And the great French hacks have been exposed
Under the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU drew a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report detailing the actions of its member states, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operation invaluable and valued for its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do the same and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to deliver on its promise of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as the reference year: international funding has been maintained and it is adding 150 million to it for three years of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
France, on the other hand, considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Development Aid d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease), to comply with its commitment regarding the financing of "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses his own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed is equal to 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be documented for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to reducing emissions, consisting in more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it as the equivalent of our commitments, but as the price of the loan (the rate of the loan to the country).
But France can only provide such a justification: it "complies" with its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% is a loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the European Union to use a loan on such a scale.
Germany demanded 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) complied with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, if the overwhelming majority of the European Union gives 1 euro to fulfill its promise, France will give only 10 centimes and considers this effort comparable.
What a lovely piece of cake!
To sum up, in its "fast start" financing, France operates with a double swindle: on the one hand, with the development of the stock over time and, on the other hand, with a real financial burden.
Although it spends only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, it can convince that it is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that even though it was Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why should Member States continue to donate when all they need to do is borrow?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not entirely naive...
The chapter on early funding is only a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not our case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to draw on the lessons learned from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounts for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and of fairness and fairness towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing long-term financing deposits (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): we will not avoid the issue of "additionality" or the way in which loans are recorded.
France should change its stance to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with the others.
So everyone is putting their hopes in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who is coming to Cancun next week.
The surprise announcement of France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans could spark an increase in the level of international trust necessary to move forward in the discussions.
