These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as confectionery, have been analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as carcinogenic, possible or likely, and five are clear carcinogenic, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptors to internally excreted (PE) glands, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Centre for Cancer Research.
“Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we see well in our research that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking.”
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain in themselves about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
An apple imported from Brazil, cited in studies as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, for which studies have found traces of potent insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, canned tuna, and even bun and chewing gum were sprinkled with pesticides and other chemicals.
